perhaps just use that for any k, `SigmakP k` is equivalent to `InP`.\n\nAlternatively, perhaps we can use that `SigmakP k` is polynomial-time equivalent to `InP`, using `P = NP`.\n\nBut no, perhaps this is trying too hard. \n\n**Another Idea:**\n\nGiven that Lean requires a proof of `SigmakP k ↔ InP`, perhaps we can do:\n\n1. For any `L`, `SigmakP k ea L → InP ea L`, and `InP ea L → SigmakP k ea L` (because for `k = 0`, they are equal; for `k ≥ 1`, since `P = NP`, `InP ea L = InNP ea L`, and perhaps `InNP ea L` implies `SigmakP 1 ea L`, etc.).\n\nBut it is not straightforward. \n\nPerhaps here is a better approach:\n\nWe can use that if `P = NP`, then `InP ea L ↔ InNP ea L`. \n\nThus, we can use this to prove that `SigmakP k ea L` is always equivalent to `InP ea L`, because:\n1. For `k = 0`, it is equal to `InP ea L`.\n2. For `k = 1`, it is `InNP ea L`, which is equivalent to `InP ea L`.\n3. For `k = 2`, it becomes complicated, but perhaps it is also equivalent to `InP ea L` because we can use `P = NP` to \"lower\" the quantifiers. \n\nBut perhaps it is easier to instead do:\n\n1. Show that `SigmakP k ea L → InP ea L`.\n2. Show that `InP ea L → SigmakP k ea L`. \n\nBut perhaps not even necessary: it suffices to prove that `SigmakP k ea L ↔ InP ea L`, because `k` was arbitrary, and then `SigmakP (k+1) ea L` also reduces to the same thing. \n\nBut perhaps we are overcomplicating.\n\nLet me try something else: \n\nFirst, we can use that if `P = NP`, then for any `ea`, the `InP ea` and `InNP ea` predicates are equivalent. \n\nNow, in Lean, `SigmakP 1 ea L` is exactly `InNP ea L`, so it becomes `InP ea L`. \n\nSimilarly, for `SigmakP 2 ea L`, we have:\n\n`∃ β, ..., (if 1 = 0 then ... else PikP 1 ...)`, but `PikP 1 ... L' = Sigma1P ... (Complement L') = InNP ... (Complement L')`, which is equivalent to `InP ... (Complement L')`. \n\nBut then, `SigmakP 2 ea L` would be `∃ β, ... , (∃ L', (InP ... (Complement L')) ∧ ...)`, etc. \n\nIt is not straightforward, but perhaps we can prove:\n\n1. If `P = NP`, then for any `k`, `SigmakP k ea L → InP ea L`. \n2. For `L ∈ P`, perhaps `L ∈ SigmakP 1 ea L`, because `InP ea L ↔ InNP ea L` and `SigmakP 1 ea L = InNP ea L`.\n\nBut perhaps this is too vague. \n\nAlternatively, perhaps we can use that `P = NP` implies that `InP ea L = InNP ea L`, so if we can show that for each `k`, `SigmakP k ea L` is a polynomial time reducible to something else, etc.\n\nBut it is getting too complex.\n\nPerhaps a better approach is to use that `P = NP`, and so `InP ea L ↔ InNP ea L`, and then use this to prove that for any `L`, and any `k`, `SigmakP k ea L` is equivalent to `InP ea L`. \n\nIn Lean terms, perhaps we can show:\n\nFor any `ea`, for any `L`, if `P = NP`, then:\n1. `SigmakP 0 ea L ↔ InP ea L` by definition.\n2. `SigmakP 1 ea L ↔ InNP ea L ↔ InP ea L`.\n3. For `k ≥ 1`, perhaps by induction we can show that `SigmakP k ea L` is equivalent to `InP ea L`.\n\nBut perhaps in Lean, we can directly use that `P = NP`, to prove the statement by strong induction on `k`.\n\n### Abstract Plan\n\nHere is a more concrete plan:\n\n1. **Base Case (`k = 0`)**:\n   - Direct from the definition of `SigmakP`: `SigmakP 0 ea L = InP ea L`.\n\n2. **Case `k = 1`**:\n   - `SigmakP 1 ea L = InNP ea L`.\n   - Since `P = NP`, `InNP ea L ↔ InP ea L`.\n\n3. **General Inductive Step (`k → k+1`)**:\n   - Assume the statement holds for `k`, i.e., for all `L`, `SigmakP k ea L ↔ InP ea L`.\n   - Then, `SigmakP (k+1) ea L` involves `∃ β, ...` and `(if k = 0 then ... else PikP k ...)`:\n     - The `if` condition is annoying, so perhaps we can split into cases:\n       - If `k = 0`, then `SigmakP 1 ea L`, which is the case above.\n       - If `k > 0`, then `(PikP k ...)` is `Sigma1P ... (Complement L')` (need to check definition).\n       - But perhaps we can avoid induction and instead directly use that `P = NP",
